body:
@aladdin-add that's really just option 1 with a different syntax. :)

@mdjermanovic

> Assuming that a shared config will document what it exports (an object, array, or function), if it's a function, config file that uses the shared config can call it with the context object and then customize the return value the same as it would customize an exported object/array?

This forces any config that is consuming the function config to also define a function config, which seems like a lot of unnecessary boilerplate to me. This is why option 2 is my least favorite of the three I thought of.

Option 3 is my current favorite assuming we want to go the route of splitting out JS-specific functionality in the future.

Just want to share I was wondering why it does work with `eslint:recommended` but doesn't work with other plugin's configs as a new way to replace `.eslintrc` `extends`.

Good to know that the special string and the example will be removed and updated to avoid this confusion:

```js
import jsdoc from "eslint-plugin-jsdoc";

export default [
  "eslint:recommendded",
  jsdoc.configs.recommended, // Example from the doc but other plugins that internally using `extends` doesn't work.
  "plugin:other-plugin/recommended", // So I tried this because the array seems to accept string like `extends` but I was wrong.
  // It was an idea also to c&p from the old `extends` to here
  {
    // ...
  }
]
```

The `FlatCompat` is really helpful in this case. I learned the difference by logging the compat output and managed to make it work either by using `FlatCompat` or rearrange those config objects.

BTW The new flat config is really nice and easier to configure.
